theorem
fixes x :: real and f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "bij f"
and h1 : "f 2 = 5"
and h2 : "\<forall> x. (inv f) (x + 4) = 2 * (inv f) x + 1"
shows  "(inv f) 17 = 23"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Given that $f(2)=5$ and $f^{-1}(x+4)=2f^{-1}(x)+1$ for all $x$, find $f^{-1}(17)$. The final Answer is 23
 ### Proof
 Note that $f(2)=5$ implies $f^{-1}(5)=2$.
 Applying $f^{-1}(x+4)=2f^{-1}(x)+1$ repeatedly, we have: \begin{align} f^{-1}(5)&=2 \\ \Rightarrow \quad f^{-1}(9)&=2f^{-1}(5)+1=5 \\ \Rightarrow \quad f^{-1}(13)&=2f^{-1}(9)+1=11 \\ \Rightarrow \quad f^{-1}(17)&=2f^{-1}(13)+1=23.
 \end{align}So $f^{-1}(17)=\boxed{23}$.
 *)
